<h2>The Mental Health Landscape for Women</h2>
<p>Women are twice as likely as men to be diagnosed with depression and anxiety disorders — a disparity that reflects both genuine biological vulnerability (hormonal influences, reproductive transitions) and differential exposure to stressors: higher rates of trauma and sexual violence, gender-based discrimination, the dual burden of professional and caregiving roles, and social pressures around appearance, body, and emotional labour.</p>

<p>Understanding these factors matters for therapy. A therapist who sees a woman's depression purely as a neurochemical event will miss the structural and contextual factors that maintain it. Good therapy holds both dimensions.</p>

<h2>Reproductive Mental Health</h2>
<p>The female reproductive lifecycle involves significant hormonal transitions that affect mental health in ways that are frequently minimised or pathologised as personal weakness rather than recognised as biological events requiring support.</p>

<p><strong>Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD):</strong> Severe, cyclical mood symptoms (dysphoria, irritability, anxiety, cognitive impairment) in the luteal phase that resolve with menstruation. PMDD is a recognised psychiatric condition with effective treatments including SSRIs and lifestyle approaches.</p>

<p><strong>Perinatal mood and anxiety disorders:</strong> Affecting 1 in 5 pregnant and postpartum women. Undertreated because of shame, fear of being seen as a "bad mother," and inadequate screening.</p>

<p><strong>Perimenopause and menopause:</strong> Hormonal changes produce mood instability, anxiety, cognitive changes, and in some women, significant depression. These symptoms are medically undertreated and often dismissed.</p>

<h2>Trauma and Safety</h2>
<p>Women experience sexual violence, intimate partner violence, and childhood sexual abuse at rates significantly higher than men. These experiences frequently produce trauma symptoms — PTSD, complex PTSD, depression, anxiety, and relationship difficulties — that require trauma-informed care.</p>

<p>A trauma-informed therapist understands the impact of gender-based trauma without minimising, sensationalising, or requiring the client to justify their experience. They approach safety, control, and disclosure at the client's pace.</p>

<h2>The Dual Burden and Exhaustion</h2>
<p>Women in most societies carry disproportionate responsibility for domestic labour and caregiving alongside professional roles — the "second shift." The psychological consequences — exhaustion, resentment, eroded sense of self, suppressed needs — are clinical concerns, not personal failures. Therapy addresses these specifically: untangling what's structural from what's internal, building capacity to advocate for oneself, and processing the complex emotions that come with the dual burden.</p>

<h2>Relationships and Emotional Labour</h2>
<p>Women are socialised to manage others' emotions — in families, friendships, and romantic relationships — often at significant cost to their own. Therapy explores the patterns that maintain over-responsibility for others' emotional states, the difficulty of prioritising one's own needs without guilt, and the relationship between social conditioning and self-abandonment.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Do I need a female therapist?</strong><br/>
Not necessarily — but preference matters. If you're dealing with gendered experiences (gender-based trauma, reproductive health, body image) and feel more comfortable with a female therapist, that preference is valid and worth honouring. The most important factors remain competence and therapeutic alliance.</p>

<p><strong>I've been told I'm "too emotional" — is there something wrong with me?</strong><br/>
No. Women's emotional expression is frequently pathologised in ways men's equivalent responses aren't. A therapist's job is to understand your emotional experience, not to assess whether it meets some arbitrary standard of appropriateness.</p>

